2023:

College Football Network National Player of the Year

CFN National Defensive Player of the Year

CFN National Defensive Lineman of the Year

HERO Sports Group of Five National Defensive Player of the Year

Walter Camp First Team All-American

Associated Press First Team All-American

Action Network First Team All-American

CFN First Team All-American

AFCA Second Team All-American

ESPN Second Team All-American

Football Writers Association of America Second Team All-American

Sporting News Second Team All-American

CBS Sports/247 Sports Second Team All-American

Phil Steele Second Team All-American

HERO Sports G5 First Team All-American

Sun Belt Conference Defensive Player of the Year

Bill Dudley Award Winner - sixth winner in JMU history

VaSID University Division Defensive Player of the Year

Touchdown Club of Richmond Defensive Lineman of the Year

Ted Hendricks Defensive End of the Year Finalist - first in JMU history

Chuck Bednarik Award Semifinalist - first in JMU history

First Team All-Sun Belt defensive lineman

VaSID University Division First Team All-State defensive lineman

JMU's Charle Haley Defensive MVP Award winner

Walter Camp National Defensive Player of the Week (Oct. 31)

CFN National Defensive Player of the Week (Oct. 1 and Oct. 22)

Sun Belt Conference Defensive Player of the Week (Oct. 23)

DC Touchdown Club College Football Player of the Week (Oct. 26)

College Football Network Midseason Defensive Lineman of the Year

The Athletic Midseason First Team All-American

CFN Midseason First Team All-American

Broke Sun Belt single-season sacks record (15.5), which is second in JMU history

Tied JMU and Sun Belt single-game record with 5.0 sacks at Marshall (Oct. 19)

Played in nine games with eight starts at defensive end

Had 50 tackles (23 solo) to go with 21 tackles for loss, 15.5 sacks, one interception for a touchdown, one pass breakup and two forced fumbles

Career-high nine tackles vs. Old Dominion (Oct. 28)

Career-high 5.5 tackles for loss at Marshall (Oct. 19)

Career-high 5.0 sacks at Marshall (Oct. 19)

Had a 24-yard pick-six vs. South Alabama (Sept. 30)

2022:

Played in all 11 games with one start at defensive end

Had 22 tackles (nine solo) to go with 6.0 tackles for loss, 2.5 sacks and one interception

Matched career-high of four tackles with a career-best 1.5 TFL vs. Middle Tennessee (Sept. 3)

Also had four tackles with a TFL at Old Dominion (Nov. 12)

Registered a full sack vs. Texas State (Oct. 1) and vs. Georgia State (Nov. 19)

Had first career interception vs. #23 Coastal Carolina (Nov. 26)

Recorded three or more tackles in three games

Made 1.0+ TFL in four outings

2021:

Played in 13 games

Had 14 tackles (five solo) to go with 2.5 tackles for loss, 2.0 sacks, one forced fumble, one pass breakup and one quarterback hurry

Season-high three tackles with a half TFL and breakup vs. Southeastern Louisiana in FCS second round (Dec. 4)

Registered a sack and forced fumble vs. Morehead State (Sept. 4)

Made two tackles at Weber State (Sept. 18) and at New Hampshire (Oct. 2)

2020-21:

Missed entire season due to injury in the fall

2019:

Played in 14 games

Had 11 tackles (four solo) to go with 2.0 tackles for loss and a half sack

Career-high four tackles vs. New Hampshire (Nov. 9)

Had two tackles against Morgan State (Sept. 14) and Richmond (Nov. 16)

Had 1.0 TFL at Rhode Island (Nov. 23) and a half sack at Elon (Sept. 28)

High School:

Washington Post First Team All-Metro as a junior and senior

First Team All-Washington Catholic Athletic Conference as a junior and senior

DC Touchdown Club member

Good Counsel’s career sacks leader, with 38.5

Set school’s single-season sacks record, with 13.0 as a senior

Helped Good Counsel to WCAC semifinals in both 2017 and 2018

Dual-sport athlete who also played basketball

Personal:

Son of Thorn and Arianne Lemon

Has a brother, Amari, and two sisters, Ariyah and Aiyana

Majoring in sport and recreation management
